\subsection{Analysis: compare the control to the drug

First, we need to access the columns of our countData that are control
and then find their mean

\NormalTok{metadata}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{dex}\OperatorTok{==}\StringTok{"control"}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## [1]  TRUE FALSE  TRUE FALSE  TRUE FALSE  TRUE FALSE
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{control.id <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{metadata[ metadata}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{dex}\OperatorTok{==}\StringTok{"control"}\NormalTok{, ]}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{id        }\CommentTok{# gives rows in metadata that match "control"}
\NormalTok{control.id}

\end{Shaded}

We look for outliers by calculating log2 fold change between treated \&
control

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{meancounts}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{log2fc <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{log2}\NormalTok{(meancounts[ , }\StringTok{"treated.mean"}\NormalTok{] }\OperatorTok{/}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{meancounts[ , }\StringTok{"control.mean"}\NormalTok{])}
\KeywordTok{head}\NormalTok{(meancounts)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
##                 control.mean treated.mean      log2fc
## ENSG00000000003       900.75       658.00 -0.45303916
## ENSG00000000005         0.00         0.00         NaN
## ENSG00000000419       520.50       546.00  0.06900279
## ENSG00000000457       339.75       316.50 -0.10226805
## ENSG00000000460        97.25        78.75 -0.30441833
## ENSG00000000938         0.75         0.00        -Inf
\end{verbatim}

NaN is returned when you do 0/0. -Inf (negative infinity) is returned
when you try to take the log of 0. We want to exclude these both.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{zero.vals <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{which}\NormalTok{(meancounts[,}\DecValTok{1}\OperatorTok{:}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{]}\OperatorTok{==}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{arr.ind=}\OtherTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{)}

\NormalTok{to.rm <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{unique}\NormalTok{(zero.vals[,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{])}
\NormalTok{mycounts <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{meancounts[}\OperatorTok{-}\NormalTok{to.rm,]}
\KeywordTok{head}\NormalTok{(mycounts)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
##                 control.mean treated.mean      log2fc
## ENSG00000000003       900.75       658.00 -0.45303916

## ENSG00000001036      2327.00      1785.75 -0.38194109
\end{verbatim}

\NormalTok{x}\OperatorTok{==}\DecValTok{0}

A common threshold used for calling something differentially expressed
is a log2(FoldChange) of greater than 2 or less than -2. Let's filter
the dataset both ways to see how many genes are up or down-regulated.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{up.ind <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{mycounts}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{log2fc }\OperatorTok{>}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{2}
\NormalTok{down.ind <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{mycounts}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{log2fc }\OperatorTok{<}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{(}\OperatorTok{-}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{)}
\KeywordTok{sum}\NormalTok{(up.ind)                                 }\CommentTok{# returns # of TRUE's (upregulated)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## [1] 250
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{sum}\NormalTok{(down.ind)                               }\CommentTok{# returns # of TRUE's (downregulated)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## [1] 367
\end{verbatim}

Now, we have our list of DE genes, but they're listed with ENSG ID's -
not very useful. Let's use a Bioconductor package to convert them to
common gene names \# Annotating Gene ID's to Gene Names \#This is done
in R console as opposed to the Rmd, so it doesn't repeat each time the
code is run: \# BiocManager::install(``AnnotationDbi'') \#

package (``org'') for Homo sapiens (``Hs''), organized as an
AnnotationDbi database package (``db''), using Entrez Gene IDs (``eg'')
as primary key. To get a list of all available key types, use: \#
columns(org.Hs.eg.db)

Now, we haven't accounted for variability at all; we've only taken
means. We have also omitted any gene that had 0 expression in either
control or treated samples, which is probably not ideal, although
according to Barry, DESeq also does this since the false positive rate
would be too high otherwise due to running so many hypotheses tests.

Thus, we'll never do it this way. We'll use DESeq2 to do these analyses
